During the NATO Summit Meetings in Lisbon, President Obama and NATO leaders focused on addressing current and future security challenges. They secured the ongoing transformation of NATO to make it more effective and capable of addressing 21st-century threats. The President also announced the beginning of a transition to Afghan lead in early 2011 and reaffirmed the Alliance's commitment to a long-term partnership with Afghanistan. NATO leaders and Russian President Medvedev agreed to strengthen the NATO-Russia relationship by expanding areas of cooperation and consultation. They also adopted a new Strategic Concept, developed a territorial missile defense capability, committed to developing critical capabilities, deepened partnerships, endorsed plans to reform the Alliance's command structure, and affirmed NATO's open-door policy for European democracies.